<dt class='comment-author ' id='c115031657792301138'>
<a name='c115031657792301138'></a>
Anonymous
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body'>
<p><I>How is it possible for experts to retrieve data once the entire disk has been rewritten with zeros?</I><BR/><BR/>Not through an OS, nor even, as I understand, via the standard read/write heads. Instead, very careful inspection of the magnetic surface is capable of retrieving "signatures" of the previous data.  That is, a 0-bit overwritten with a 1 is magnetically slightly different from a 1 overwritten with a 1.<BR/><BR/>There is also the possibility of very slight physical misalignments between successive writes, again creating zones much smaller than a regular 1 or 0 domain where the old data may live on.<BR/><BR/>Google for SQUID (Super Cooled Quantum Interference Device) to learn more.</p>
</dd>
