<dt class='comment-author ' id='c115074045711121892'>
<a name='c115074045711121892'></a>
Anonymous
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body'>
<p>One pass of all zeroes is sufficient to prevent any data recovery just using the drive.  If you've written a zero to a sector, then the drive will return a zero when that sector is read.<BR/><BR/>Yes, it's possible to get data back by disassembling a drive and using exotic techniques (magnetic force microscopy) on it.  The person buying your old hd is unlikely to have this equipment in his basement.<BR/><BR/>Unless you expect national intelligence agencies to be after your old hd, one pass of zeroes will suffice.</p>
</dd>
<dd class='comment-footer'>
<span class='comment-timestamp'>
<a href='http://linuxhelp.blogspot.com/2006/06/how-to-securely-erase-hard-disk-before.html?showComment=1150740420000#c115074045711121892' title='comment permalink'>
