<dt class='comment-author ' id='c7143846111463862320'>
<a name='c7143846111463862320'></a>
RTFM-2
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body'>
<p>^^ nice post "someone who...", a rare moment of sanity in the TV-soap world of "experts".<BR/><BR/>Having done drive recovery 8hrs daily now for about 6 years, fulltime job, you're damn right.<BR/><BR/>What isn't commonly known is we do drive recovery AFTER zero runs by simply using an analog signal from the heads (not microscopy), eg: you say "write a zero" drive says "yeah, ok" and tries to take the magnetic signature down to zero form that spot. Because of remanance, it won't go down to absolute zero signal, but maybe "0.3" still well below the "cutoff of halfway plus a safety-zone in the middle where u treat it as indeterminate"-range. In recovery, by assuming that 0.3 used to be a "high" and 0.1 used to be a "low", u can make a good stab at the original data. U simply amplify the head output with an amp back to normal ranges<BR/>There you go, a $5000-per disk "recovery service" explained in a nutshell<BR/><BR/>After that, dd rules :)<BR/><BR/>"look what they did to my porn ma!"</p>
</dd>
